<p class="drop-cap">When the Holy Spirit descended at Pentecost, He did not descend upon isolated individuals. He descended upon a community, a group of people gathered in one place, praying with one mind. The Church, in Eastern understanding, was not founded by an organizational charter or a theological manifesto. It was born in a room full of fire, and it has been burning ever since.</p>

<p>Eastern Christianity does not think of the Church primarily as an institution, a hierarchy, or a set of beliefs you sign up for. It thinks of the Church as a living organism, the Body of Christ, animated by the Holy Spirit, extending through time and space. The Church is not an organization that <em>has</em> a spiritual dimension. It is a spiritual reality that <em>takes</em> organizational form.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— St. Ignatius of Antioch, Letter to the Smyrnaeans, c. 110 AD">
  Where the bishop is, there is the Church — just as where Christ is, there is the catholic Church.
</Pullquote>

<h2>Conciliarity: How the Church Decides</h2>

<p>One of the most visible differences between Eastern and Western Christianity is how authority works. In the West, the Bishop of Rome, the Pope, holds a unique position of universal jurisdiction. He can define doctrine, overrule bishops, and govern the entire Church from a single center.</p>

<p>The East has never operated this way.</p>

<p>Eastern ecclesiology is built on the principle of <strong>conciliarity</strong> (from the Greek <em>synodality</em>, literally "walking together"). Decisions are made not by a single authority but by the gathered bishops of the Church, meeting in council, guided by the Holy Spirit. The model is the Council of Jerusalem described in Acts 15, where the Apostles and elders gathered to resolve a dispute about whether Gentile converts needed to follow Jewish law. The resolution was framed not as a papal decree but as a communal discernment: "It seemed good to the Holy Spirit and to us."</p>

<p>That phrase, <em>it seemed good to the Holy Spirit and to us</em>, is the template for how Eastern Christianity believes the Church should govern itself.</p>

<p>The seven Ecumenical Councils (from Nicaea I in 325 to Nicaea II in 787) are the supreme expression of this principle. They defined the core doctrines of the faith: the Trinity, the two natures of Christ, the veneration of icons. Not by papal fiat but by the consensus of bishops drawn from across the Christian world.</p>

