<h2>The Bishop of Rome</h2>

<p>It would be dishonest to discuss Eastern ecclesiology without addressing the papacy. Eastern Christians, whether Orthodox or Eastern Catholic, have a complex relationship with papal authority.</p>

<p>The East has never denied that the Bishop of Rome holds a position of honor. The ancient formula was "first among equals" (<em>primus inter pares</em>). Rome was the see of Peter and Paul, the capital of the empire, and its bishop was traditionally given a primacy of honor: the right to convene councils, to hear appeals, to speak first.</p>

<p>What the East has resisted, consistently, is the claim that this primacy extends to <em>universal jurisdiction</em>. The power to govern other bishops' dioceses, to define doctrine unilaterally, or to override the decisions of ecumenical councils. For the East, the head of the Church is Christ, and no single bishop, however venerable, can serve as His vicar on earth in a way that diminishes the authority of the college of bishops as a whole.</p>

<p>This is a real and unresolved disagreement. It contributed to the Great Schism of 1054 and remains one of the primary obstacles to full reunion between East and West. But the conversation is ongoing, and Eastern Catholics, who are in full communion with Rome, represent a living experiment in how Eastern conciliarity and Western papal authority might coexist.</p>

<h2>The Three Orders</h2>

<p>Eastern Christianity, like Western Christianity, has a threefold ordained ministry: bishops, priests, and <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#deacon">deacons</a>. But the emphasis and practice differ in important ways.</p>

<p><strong>The Bishop</strong> is the fullness of the priesthood. Successor of the Apostles, chief liturgist of his diocese, teacher, and guardian of the faith. Every celebration of the <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#divine-liturgy">Divine Liturgy</a> is, in theological principle, a celebration <em>by the bishop</em>, even when a priest presides in his place.</p>

<p><strong>The Priest</strong> (often called "Father") is the bishop's representative in the parish. He celebrates the Liturgy, administers the sacraments, teaches, and cares for souls. In the Eastern tradition, married men may be ordained priests, a practice that dates to the earliest centuries of the Church. Bishops, however, are drawn from the ranks of celibate clergy or widowed priests.</p>

<p><strong>The <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#deacon">Deacon</a></strong> is the most visible minister in the Liturgy. He leads the litanies (the responsive prayers), proclaims the Gospel, directs the congregation's attention ("Let us attend!"), and assists the priest at the altar. Bridge between the sanctuary and the people.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— St. Cyprian of Carthage, On the Unity of the Church, 3rd century">
  The bishop is in the Church and the Church is in the bishop, and if anyone is not with the bishop, that one is not in the Church.
</Pullquote>

<h2>The Local Parish as the Church in Fullness</h2>

<p>Here is perhaps the most counterintuitive claim in Eastern ecclesiology: the local parish, gathered around its priest (who represents the bishop), celebrating the <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#divine-liturgy">Divine Liturgy</a> on a Sunday morning, <em>is</em> the Church. Not a branch office. Not a franchise. Not a local chapter of a global organization. The Church in its fullness.</p>

<p>This does not mean that individual parishes are independent or self-governing. They exist in communion with their bishop, with the other parishes of the diocese, and with the wider Church across the world. But the theological point is that the Church is not fundamentally a global bureaucracy that trickles down to the local level. It is fundamentally a eucharistic assembly, a community gathered around the Body and Blood of Christ, and every such assembly contains the whole mystery of the Church.</p>

