<h2>The <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#royal-doors">Royal Doors</a> and the Liturgical Space</h2>

<p>The architecture of an Eastern church embodies this theology. The building is divided into three spaces: the <strong>narthex</strong> (the entrance), the <strong>nave</strong> (where the congregation stands), and the <strong>sanctuary</strong> (behind the iconostasis, where the altar stands). Three spaces corresponding to a theological progression: the world, the Church, and heaven.</p>

<p>The <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#royal-doors">Royal Doors</a>, the central doors of the iconostasis, are not merely functional. They represent the boundary between earth and heaven. When the priest emerges through the Royal Doors carrying the Gospel or the Eucharist, it is understood as a revelation: heaven opening, Christ coming out to meet His people.</p>

<p>The congregation stands facing east, toward the rising sun, which is an ancient symbol of the risen Christ. The entire building is oriented toward the encounter with God that takes place in the Liturgy. Nothing is decorative. Everything is theological.</p>

<h2>Many Members, One Body</h2>

<p>The Church, in Eastern understanding, is not a club you join or a belief system you subscribe to. It is a living Body, St. Paul's metaphor, taken with full seriousness. Each member has a role: the bishop teaches, the priest sanctifies, the deacon serves, the cantor sings, the iconographer paints, the grandmother prays. No role is more important than another, because a body needs all its members.</p>

<p>And this Body extends beyond the living. The saints who have died are still members of the Church. The icons on the walls are not decorations. They are windows into the communion of saints, reminders that the Church includes both the living and the dead, the visible and the invisible, those who worship on earth and those who worship in heaven.</p>

<p>The next step explores the means by which this Body is sustained: the seven Mysteries (sacraments) through which heaven meets earth, and ordinary things like water, oil, bread, and wine become vehicles of divine life.</p>

